NATION; 
</P>
<P>
DEAVER DROPS APPEAL OF PERJURY CONVICTIONS, CITES FINANCIAL BURDEN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Former White House aide Michael K. Deaver today abandoned his appeal of perjury 
convictions for lying about his lobbying, saying he wanted to "put this period 
of my life behind me." 
</P>
<P>
The former top adviser to former President Ronald Reagan and a close friend of 
the former First Family said he is dropping the appeal "with the firm belief 
that I was not guilty of the charges of which I was convicted." Deaver also 
said he could not continue the "financial burden" of the appeal process. 
</P>
<P>
His lawyers have said that Deaver, a recovering alcoholic, is unable to find 
work. The investigation by an independent counsel forced Deaver to close his 
lobbying business. In 1986, the height of his lobbying career, Deaver had an 
income of $527,958. 
</P>
</TEXT>
